  title `Page 6`
  content obj_root_law_sections_6_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes
  sourcePage 6
obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line 6
  line `( b ) arising out of transactions in securities entered into after the 1st day of April, 1991, and on or`
  line `before the 6th day of June, 1992, in which a person notified under sub - section ( 2 ) of section 3 is`
  line `involved as a party, broker, intermediary or in any other manner.`
  line `( 2 ) Every suit, claim or other legal proceeding (other than an appeal) pending before any court`
  line `immediately before the commencement of the Special Court (Trial of Offences Relating to Transactions`
  line `in Securities) Amendment Act, 1994 (24 of 1994), being a suit, claim or proceeding, the cause of action`
  line `whereon it is based is such that it would have been, if it had arisen after such commencement, within the`
  line `jurisdiction of the Special Court under sub - section ( 1 ), shall stand transferred on such commencement to`
  line `the Special Court and the Special Court may, on receipt of the records of such suit, claim or other legal`
  line `proceeding, proceed to deal with it, so far as may be, in the same manner as a suit, claim or legal`
  line `proceeding from the stage which was reached before such transfer or from any earlier stage or de novo as`
  line `the Special Court may deem fit.`
  line `( 3 ) On and from the commencement of the Special Court (Trial of Offences Relating to Transactions`
  line `in S ecurities) Amendment Act, 1994 (24 of 1994), no court other than the Special Court shall have, or be`
  line `entitled to exercise, any jurisdiction, power or authority in relation to any matter or claim referred to in`
  line `sub - section ( 1 ).`
  line `( 4 ) While dealing with cases relating to any matter or claim under this section, the Special Court shall`
  line `not be bound by the procedure laid down by the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), but shall be`
  line `guided by the principles of natural justice, and subject to the other provisions of this Act and of any rules,`
  line `the Special Court shall have power to regulate its own procedure.`
  line `( 5 ) Without prejudice to the other powers conferred under this Act, the Special Court shall have, for`
  line `the purposes of discharging its functions under this section, the same powers as are vested in a civil court`
  line `under the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), while trying a suit, in respect of the following`
  line `matters, namely: —`
  line `( a ) summoning and enforcing the attendance of any person and examining him on oath;`
  line `( b ) requiring the discovery and production of documents;`
  line `( c ) receiving evidence on affidavits;`
  line `( d ) subject to the provisions of sections 123 and 124 of the Indian Evidence Act, 1872`
  line `(1 of 1872), requisitioning any public record or document or copy of such record or document from`
  line `any office;`
  line `( e ) issuing commissions for the examination of witnesses or documents;`
  line `( f ) reviewing its decisions;`
  line `( g ) dismissing a case for default or deciding it ex parte;`
  line `( h ) setting aside any order of dismissal of any case for default or any order passed by it ex parte;`
  line and
  line `( i ) a ny other matter which may be prescribed by the Central Government under sub - section ( 1 ) of`
  line `section 14.`
  line `9 B. Powers of the Special Court in arbitration matters. — ( 1 ) The Special Court shall have the`
  line `jurisdiction and powers of a Court conferred under the Arbitration Act, 1940 (10 of 1940) to decide any`
  line `question forming subject matter of a reference relating to any matter or claim mentioned in sub - section`
  line `( 1 ) of section 9 A.`
  line `( 2 ) Every suit or other proceeding (other than an appeal) in relation to any matter or claim referred to`
  line `in sub - section ( 1 ) of section 9 A pending before any Court and governed by the Arbitration Act, 1940`
  line `(10 of 1940), immediately before the date of commencement of the Special Court (Trial of Offences`
  line `Relating to Transactions in Securities) Amendment Act, 1994 (24 of 1994) shall stand transferred on that`
  line `date to the Special Court.`
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_7:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-7
  sectionNo (7)
  orderNo 7
  title `Page 7`
  content obj_root_law_sections_7_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes
  sourcePage 7
obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line 7
  line `Explanation. — For the purposes of this section, the expressions “Court” and “reference” shall have`
  line `respectively the same meanings as defined under clauses ( c ) and ( e ) of section 2 of the Arbitration Act,`
  line `1940 (10 of 1940 ). ]`
  line `10. Appeal. — ( 1 ) Notwit hstanding anything in the Code 1 [or the Code of Civil Procedure,1908`
  line `(5 of 1908) or the Arbitration Act, 1940 (19 of 1940)], an appeal shall lie from any judgment 1 [, decree]`
  line `sentence or order, not being interlocutory order, of the Special Court to the Supreme Court both on facts`
  line `and on law.`
  line `( 2 ) Except as aforesaid, no appeal or revision shall lie to any Court from any judgment 1 [, decree]`
  line `sentence or order of the Special Court.`
  line `( 3 ) Every appeal under this section shall be preferred within a period of thirty days from the date of`
  line `any judgment, sentence or order of the Special Court:`
  line `Provided that the Supreme Court may entertain an appeal after the expiry of the said period of thirty`
  line `days if it is satisfied that the appellant had sufficient cause for not preferring the appeal within the period`
  line `of thirty days.`
  line `11. Discharge of liabilities. — ( 1 ) Notwithstanding anything contained in the Code and any other law`
  line `for the time being in force, the Special Court may make such order as it may deem fit directing the`
  line `Custodian for the disposal of the property under attachment.`
  line `( 2 ) The following liabilities shall be paid or discharged in full, as far as may be, in the order as`
  line `under: —`
  line `( a ) all revenues, taxes, cesses and rates due from the persons notified by the Custodian under`
  line `sub - section ( 2 ) of section 3 to the Central Government or any State Government or any local`
  line authority;
  line `( b ) all amounts due from the person so notified by the Custodian to any bank or financial`
  line `institution or mutual fund;`
  line `( c ) any other liability as may be specified by the Special Court from time to time.`
  line `2 [ 11 A. Power to punish for contempt. — The Special Court shall have, and exercise, the same`
  line `jurisdiction, powers and authority in respect of contempt of itself as a High Court has and may exercise`
  line `and, for this purpose, the provisions of the Contempt of Courts Act, 1971 (70 of 1971), shall have effect`
  line `subject to the modifications that —`
  line `( a ) the references therein to a High Court shall be construed as including a reference to such`
  line `Special Court;`
  line `( b ) the references to the Advocate - General in section 15 of the said Act, shall be construed, in`
  line `relation to the Special Court, as a reference to the Attorney - General or the Solicitor - General or the`
  line `Additional Solicitor - General. ]`
  line `12. Protection of action taken in good faith. — ( 1 ) No suit, prosecution or other legal proceeding`
  line `shall lie against the Central Government or the Custodian for anything which is in good faith done or`
  line `intended to be done under this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) No suit or other legal proceeding shall lie against the Central Government or any of its officers or`
  line `other employees for any damage caused or likely to be caused by anything which is in good faith done or`
  line `intended to be done under this Act.`
  line `13. Act to have overriding effect. — The provisions of this Act shall have effect notwithstanding`
  line `anything inconsistent therewith contained in any other law for the time being in force or in any instrument`
  line `having effect by virtue of any law, other than this Act, or in any decree or order of any court, tribunal or`
  line `other authority.`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 24 of 1994, s. 4 (w.e.f. 25 - 1 - 1994).`
  line `2. Ins. by s. 5, ibid. (w.e.f. 25 - 1 - 1994).`
obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_8:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-8
  sectionNo (8)
  orderNo 8
  title `Page 8`
  content obj_root_law_sections_8_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes
  sourcePage 8
obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line 8
  line `14. Power to make rules. — ( 1 ) The Central Government may, by notification in the O f ficial Gazette,`
  line `make rules for carrying out the provisions of this Act.`
  line `( 2 ) Every rule made by the Central Government under this Act shall be laid, as soon as may be after it`
  line `is made, before each House of Parliament, while it is in session, for a total period of thirty days which`
  line `may be comprised in one session or in two or more successive sessions, and if, before the expiry of the`
  line `session immediately following the session or the successive sessions aforesaid, both Houses agree in`
  line `making any modification in the rule or both Houses agree that the rule should not be made, the rul e shall`
  line `thereafter have effect only in such modified form or be of no effect, as the case may be; so, however, that`
  line `any such modification or annulment shall be without prejudice to the validity of anything previously done`
  line `under that rule.`
  line `15. Repeal and savings. — ( 1 ) The Special Court (Trial of Offences Relating to Transactions in`
  line `Securities) Ordinance, 1992 (Ord. 10 of 1992) is hereby repealed.`
  line `( 2 ) Notwithstanding such repeal, anything done or any action taken under the said Ordinance, shall be`
  line `deemed to have been done or taken under the corresponding provisions of this Act.`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_9:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-9
  sectionNo (9)
  orderNo 9
  title `Page 9`
  content obj_root_law_sections_9_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes
  sourcePage 9
obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line 9
  line `STATEMENT OF OBJECTS AND REASONS`
  line `In the course of the investigations by the Reserve Bank of India, large scale irregularities and`
  line `malpractices were noticed in transactions, in both the Government and other securities, indulged in by`
  line `some brokers in collusion with the employees of various banks and financial institutions. The said`
  line `irregularities and malpractices led to the diversion of funds from banks and financial institutions to the`
  line `individual accounts of certain brokers.`
  line `2. To deal with the situation and in particular to ensure the speedy recovery of the huge amount`
  line `involved, to punish the guilty and restore confidence in and maintain the basic integrity and credibility of`
  line `the banks and financial institutions the Special Court (Trial of Offences Relating to Transactions in`
  line `Securities) Ordinance, 1992 was promulgated on the 6th June, 1992. The Ordinance provides for the`
  line `establishment of a Special Court with a sitting Judge of a High Court for speedy trial of offences relatin g`
  line `to transactions in securities and disposal of properties attached. It also provides for appointment of one or`
  line `more Custodians for attaching the property of the offenders with a view to prevent diversion of such`
  line `properties by the offenders.`
  line `3. The Bill seeks to replace the said Ordinance.`
  line `N EW D ELHI. MANMOHAN SINGH.`
  line `The 7 th July, 1992.`
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
